TopicTitle: [1.2.2] Realistic Progression Zero (RP-0) - Lightweight RealismOverhaul career v0.53 June 12

Articles.Content:
Hey, sorry for almost double posting, but I need help

I would like to hear some useful tips about rocket building...

I am already in RP-0 for some time, and I succeeded getting my first satellite into orbit. I tried advancing further, launching heavier payloads into orbit, but no matter how I build the rocket, It always has the same DV and almost always fails to complete it's mission.

1 hour ago, Djolox said:

Hey, sorry for almost double posting, but I need help

I would like to hear some useful tips about rocket building...

I am already in RP-0 for some time, and I succeeded getting my first satellite into orbit. I tried advancing further, launching heavier payloads into orbit, but no matter how I build the rocket, It always has the same DV and almost always fails to complete it's mission.

The 1st few tiers are very unforgiving, i suggest unlocking the vanguard booster, AJ10 , baby Sargent SRB, vangaurd 1 probe core and the "5 ton avionics core" (able or delta i forget which). These parts make with a procedural fairing and procedural decoupler make for a good launch platform for early comms/science satilites ...as vanguard one with 1 of each of re-run-able science sensors and a communitron 16 is very light  and its built in solar panels will handle all the power draw. Aim for total mass of 9999kg (10,000kg as long as you dont get an avionics warning). Upper most stage (inside a fairing) is the probe payload & baby Sargent SRB "kick" stage that fires at AP (of 160km to 200km) that finishes orbit, the 2nd last stage is the AJ10, a single 5 ton capable avionics core, that with itself and final payload is under 5000Kg (you want this stage to have a TWR of 1.0+ and to aim for this stage to finish as you hit your AP being 100% level at horizon line, this is because final stage is unguided and is assisted greatly being level inside the prograde marker on navball), the first stage is the vangaurd booster and another 5 ton capable avionics core using up the rest of your 10000Kg mass limit. this should have somewhere around 9200 Dv. This is basicly a clone of the real life Vangaurd. i can supply a pic if you need

 

this should provide a good design basics showing that payload mass can greatly effect size of rocket

Edited December 31, 2015 by Guest

19 hours ago, Djolox said:

Guys, what do you think about BD Adjustable Landing Gear compatibility? I tried it, but I ran into compatibility problems. The Wheels were instantly overheating on the runway and exploding almost instantly after engine startup. I found it is the problem with the low default temperature of gears! External temperature is 300K and external is 1730K. The problem is that I don't know how to change it.

There's a known issue with the BD adjustable gear. We're looking into it, but it's an RO issue (to do with the part cfg) not placement or pricing.
For now replace your RealismOverhaul/RO_SuggestedMods/BahamutoD/Adjustable Landing Gear.cfg file with this one:

https://github.com/KSP-RO/RealismOverhaul/raw/master/GameData/RealismOverhaul/RO_SuggestedMods/BahamutoD/Adjustable%20Landing%20Gear.cfg
and see if it helps.

Welp, totally forgot to bump the OP's version. We're on .42 now.

  • Place and price CryoEngines mod.
  • Make crewed Mars/Venus flyby contracts declinable.

On 12/30/2015 at 1:43 PM, Workable Goblin said:

Well, I can see part of your problem. It is far easier to reach Mach 1+ at higher altitudes like 8,000 or 9,000 meters where the air is thinner and there's less drag; reaching Mach 1 at low altitudes like 1-2,000 meters is more for showing off. Additionally, you can use the potential energy of high altitude to break Mach 1 in a dive (which is what early jets had to do, anyways).

I designed a jet that can reach Mach 1(.075) in level flight (going by FAR's Mach meter; that corresponds to a speed of about 323 m/s), and can easily complete the contract by going into a dive. I just fired up KSP, took some screenshots, and put them together in an imgur album for you:

 

Craft file available?

Yes. 

ship = X-2A Peregrine
version = 1.0.5
description = The X-2 was the second major project of the International Aerospace Development Agency, and was intended to be the first jet aircraft to break the speed of sound in level flight through the use of innovative aerodynamic concepts like the all-moving tailplane first demonstrated on Britain's Miles M.52 test aircraft or highly swept wings and tail surfaces.¨¨The X-2A was a redesigned version of the X-2 with a number of major changes intended to allow it to reach its original design mandate of achieving the speed of sound in level flight. Comparison with the XD-1 Bug high-speed drone, which had been able to reach Mach 1 in level flight, had shown that the X-2 was hampered by an excessive cross-sectional area and high wave-drag values that prevented its relatively weak engines from reaching the desired speeds.¨¨The aircraft was named after the peregrine falcon, the fastest bird in the world.

to match planes:

1: build craft and roll it out to pad,

2: go to vessel on pad and LOCK Batteries

3: use KER or MJ to see relative inclination to moon, time warp until its under 0.3 degrees, UNLOCK BATTERIES & launch

4: watch relative incline on way to orbit adjusting to keep it around 0.3 degrees or less

5: once your in orbit you will be aprox inline with the moon (good enough to impact it or fly by it)

** getting inline with moon isnt too bad, but without avionics control flying by or hitting it can be abit of trial and error.... with the right ascent profile and Dv, you will be in an orbit that will intersect the moon "eventually"... i use the vanguard 1 probe with some science instruments and communitron 16 on it... it can atleast communicate  and power itself  indefinitely until flyby or impact. waiting for more tech will make it easier, but the same tech nodes that that have the vangaurd 1 probe and the vangaurd booster/AJ10/baby sargent  can impact/flyby moon with some pratice

On 12/30/2015 at 3:17 PM, Djolox said:

Hey, sorry for almost double posting, but I need help

I would like to hear some useful tips about rocket building...

I am already in RP-0 for some time, and I succeeded getting my first satellite into orbit. I tried advancing further, launching heavier payloads into orbit, but no matter how I build the rocket, It always has the same DV and almost always fails to complete it's mission.

On 12/30/2015 at 3:17 PM, Djolox said:

 

Hey Djolox! (and other folks on the forum :-) ) I am going to jump in on this question.. and I am assuming you are talking about a simple, solid stack rocket without side boosters.

Ok its important to note, there are a few things that are handy to more easily put things into orbit using RP-0 in the early game. You can do it with a lot less, but you really have to understand not only Delta V implications, but also TWR/SLT considerations, and also that you only have one ignition on any main engine in the early game.

1) RCS. Any sort of RCS!! Try to get Hydrazine for second stage maneuvering, as that is the most powerful in the early game. You can put on RCS thrusters and a hydrazine tank on your second stage to keep it in alignment for your circularization burn. I usually put them on a procedural tank, sized smaller than the stage, and use an interstage fairing to reduce aero drag, however you can also attach them onto a procedural structural fuselage and do the same thing, if you want to include your hydrazine in a main tank setup, and still use a fairing.

2) Ullage thrusters. Make sure to add a cluster of 1Kn thrusters (they are in the engines part section) once you unlock them to all single ignition main engine setups above stage 1.. most engines in RP-0 are subject to Ullage. You can use RCS thrusters as well for this, but it takes more skill and time. Keep in mind RCS and the 1Kn thrusters can both use hydrazine, so use that to your advantage to save weight. Also its nice that the 1Kn thrusters surface attach in symmetry mode out of the box.. you don't need to use radial attachment points or thruster plates. This is a great weight saver.

Ok as far as your Delta V woes.. there is a reason they call it "The Tyranny Of The Rocket Equation" :-) It takes about 10-11k Delta V (technically, it is 9.4k but... you have to be really precise!) to put something in a an orbit around Earth if everything is perfect.. but of course it isn't for us!  If you can get 11k Delta V, you should be able to get anything into an LEO. I would try starting at 150km orbit with 11k Delta V.

To get 11k Delta V, you may need three stages in the early game. What you want is the most powerful first stage main engine that can give you about half your delta V budget, an efficient second stage with something like 50% of remaining, and a third with the remaining 50%, so something like 5500/2750/2750 or there about. You also should think about TWR on your second stage being greater than 1, as you may need to tip it up or down during your burn to adjust your apoapsis approach if you didn't have a perfect first stage path. I accomplish this with using multiple engines. This gives a slight penalty on Delta V though, so watch the numbers. The third stage should be the very most efficient engine you can get for vacuum, whatever it is. It is also useful if it is the lightest.

If you have a need to do in space maneuvering, RCS combined with 1Kn thrusters can't be beat. The 1Kn thrusters can ignite anytime to give power (but are not throittleable) and the RCS can give you fine control. I use the 1Kn thrusters on a service module to do deorbiting and rendezvous maneuvers, as well as orbital/interplanetary corrections of more then 100m/s.

Engines have weight! If you switch out one engine for another, it may not show much in the upper stage delta V it is attached to.. in fact you may see a boost in upper stage delta V from switching an engine, but in first and/or second stage you could lose hundreds of meters per second to engine weight in an upper stage so you'll have to experiment to see if a lighter, less efficient engine makes more sense for an upper stage for your design.

It is all about weight! (well.. mass technically). remove your first and second  stages and record the weight of the third stage.. then the first and second stage.

FInally, a big problem is that many people still tend to get into a flight path that is too steep for larger payloads, but fine for light ones. Delta V is over time, and the higher the mass, the longer it takes to move it. In the early game, you don't have a lot of TWR in upper stages usually, so the less TWR you have in an upper stage, the flatter your path needs to be to give you more time to burn delta V to get to orbit. I typically use a 30% path with an early turn (at 100- 150m/s... this makes a LOT of difference.. play with this number). That still makes it pretty hairy (as you burn through the atmosphere), but I have been able to consistently launch capsules into a polar orbit at about 250km with 11.5K delta V after testing a few flight path iterations.

If you want to know ahead of time what is more efficient, thats related to the ISP of an engine. The higher the better. For first stages, look at ISP (ASL). For second and above, look at  ISP (Vac). 5 points makes a difference.. 10 points makes a huge difference, especially down around the 300 area.

If you want side boosters, it may be better to leave off the main engine while they are firing. If their TWR is less than about 1.5 without the main engine, then fire them at the same time as the main engine. I wouldn't have your TWR for first stage be more than 1.5 or so, otherwise you can get into stability problems later on as your flight path deviates too much from a smooth arc and you kill 1000m/s on steering and aero losses. However, if you really want to try using solid or liquid boosters and high TWR at launch, you'll need to think about higher orbits than LEO, since in the early game you can't throttle down to avoid enormous dynamic pressure in atmosphere. In fact, if you do that, you may even be able to scale down your central core to a TWR of 1.00 or less at launch (by itself) if you use good bossters. It's all about balance.

 

I hope this helps! There really isn't a one stop answer to your question... perhaps people can post craft files? :-)

 

PS: Here is scott Manley showing off his early game launcher. Maybe it will give you some ideas! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hrWRimhjCyU

I usually start out with the ideal delta V for an orbit (ignoring atmosphere) and go from there.
